    "updated_at": "2023-10-22T09:50:06Z",
    "body": "I have been tinkering with zsh to see what is possible. It is possible to override the zle widgets that are called whenever a character is inserted or deleted and to redraw the prompt on these events. \r\n\r\n```zsh\r\nfunction configure_starship() {\r\n    local BUFFER=$@\r\n    # If buffer contains kubectl, enable kubernetes module\r\n    if [[ $BUFFER == *\"kubectl\"* ]]; then\r\n      starship config kubernetes.disabled false\r\n    else\r\n      starship config kubernetes.disabled true\r\n    fi\r\n}\r\n\r\nfunction zle-line-pre-redraw {\r\n  if [[ $KEYS_QUEUED_COUNT  -eq 0 ]]; then\r\n    configure_starship $BUFFER\r\n    zle reset-prompt\r\n  fi\r\n}\r\n\r\nzle -N zle-line-pre-redraw\r\n```\r\n\r\nFor now I am editing the starship.toml directly, but if the feature were to be integrated in starship, the `prompt` subcommand would take a `--commands` with the list of binaries in the parsed command line. It could then deduce which modules to show based on some `detect_commands` attribute in the starship.toml.\r\nIt would thus be the role of each shell to expand aliases and parse the command line before calling starship. I have not checked if other shells have the same capabilities as zsh to implement this feature, but I would guess it must be the case for the most mainstream ones.\r\nDoes anyone else feel like it could be a good idea to explore ?\r\n",
